ity, the history of the suburbs is not simply a history of competing urban forms; rather, it is a history of alternatives that advocated collective solutions over the dominant model of single-family home ownership and car-dominated spaces.  afunded by University of Toronto Libraries  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCity planningxHistoryy20th centuryzCzech RepubliczPrague. 0aCity planningxHistoryy20th centuryzOntariozToronto. 0aNational socialism and architecturezCzech RepubliczPrague. 0aNational socialism and architecturezOntariozToronto. 0aSuburbsxHistoryy20th centuryzCzech RepubliczPrague. 0aSuburbsxHistoryy20th centuryzOntariozToronto. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / Urban.2bisacsh  ahome ownership.  ahousing estate.  amodernism.  amodernist architecture.  asocialism.  asuburban landscape.  asuburban planning.  asuburbs.  aurbanism.2 aUniversity of Toronto Librariesefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311127253508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069045340uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781487541385zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487541385zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781487541385/original  a978-3-11-069045-3 University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  a978-3-11-127253-5 ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA